            <fr:addr type="user">Cauchy-Hadamard Theorem</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>Cauchy-Hadamard Theorem.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Cauchy-Hadamard Theorem">Cauchy-Hadamard Theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>25</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Gives us a precise way to determine the <fr:strong>radius of <fr:link type="external" href="convergence">convergence</fr:link></fr:strong> of a <fr:link type="local" href="power%20series.xml" addr="power series" title="Power series">power series</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For a <fr:link type="local" href="power%20series.xml" addr="power series" title="Power series">power series</fr:link> centered at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_0]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\sum _{n=0}^\infty  a_n (z - z_0)^n = a_0 + a_1(z - z_0) + a_2(z - z_0)^2 + \dots ]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_n]]></fr:tex> are the complex coefficients, the radius of convergence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is given by the formula:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\frac {1}{R} = \limsup _{n \to  \infty } |a_n|^{\frac {1}{n}}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Where <fr:link type="external" href="limsup">limsup</fr:link> here is the usual sense in <fr:link type="external" href="Functional%20Analysis">Functional Analysis</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Has an analogue of the for the singular part of the <fr:link type="local" href="Laurent%20series.xml" addr="Laurent series" title="Laurent series">Laurent series</fr:link>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_0 \in  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{a_k\} \subset  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>. Given the series of negative powers (it's a power series)</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\sum _{k=1}^{+\infty } {a_k {(z-z_0)}^k}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r:=\limsup _{k \to  +\infty } {|a_k|}^{\frac {1}{k}}]]></fr:tex>. Let</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>293</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">Complex power series</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>Complex power series.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Complex power series">Complex power series</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>25</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Given a <fr:link type="local" href="complex%20sequence.xml" addr="complex sequence" title="Complex sequence">complex sequence</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{a_k\} \subset  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_0 \in  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>The <fr:strong>power series</fr:strong> of center <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_0]]></fr:tex> and coefficients <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_k]]></fr:tex> is defined by</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f(z) = \sum _{k=0}^{+\infty } {a_k (z-z_0)^k}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is defined for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> such that the <fr:link type="local" href="power%20series.xml" addr="power series" title="Power series">power series</fr:link> converges.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Recall that there are 3 possible cases:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>The series converges only at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z = z_0]]></fr:tex> This happens when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_k]]></fr:tex> is very large, e.g. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_k = k!]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>The series converges everywhere e.g. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z_0 = 0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_k = \frac {1}{k!}]]></fr:tex> and the series is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum {\frac {z^k}{k!}}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\exists  R \in  (0, +\infty )]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:ol><fr:li>there is absulute convergence in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\left \{ |z-z_0| < R \right \}]]></fr:tex></fr:li> <fr:li>No convergence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\left \{ |z-z_0| > R \right \}]]></fr:tex></fr:li> <fr:li>On the boundary we cannot say</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:li></fr:ol>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
